{
  "answer": "**The verse work is *Elene* by Cynewulf, Chapter 1.**[^1]\n\nThis Old English poem recounts Constantine's mother Elene's quest to find the True Cross. The closing passage begins by lamenting an aged man \"tossed by waves of care,\" who \"in the mead-hall received treasures, appled gold\" and once rode a horse that \"measured the mile-paths before him, proudly prancing, adorned with wires,\" before all joy waned.[^2] It then shifts to an eschatological prophecy of judgment by fire, explicitly dividing souls into three ranks: the righteous \"uppermost in that fire,\" the sinful tormented \"in the middle, covered with soot,\" and the accursed plunged \"in the fire’s depths,\" down \"into hell’s abyss.\"[^3]\n\n[^1]: Cynewulf, *Elene*, [Chapter 1](/works/cynewulf-elene-d2d132/01/translation/).\n\n[^2]: Cynewulf, *Elene*, [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-elene-d2d132/01/translation/#p-8f8a1b).\n\n[^3]: Cynewulf, *Elene*, [paragraph](/works/cynewulf-elene-d2d132/01/translation/#p-dcbbfe).",
